
ICU MORTALITY PREDICTION - RESULTS SUMMARY

DATASET: 15,000 ICU patients
FEATURES: Age, heart rate, temperature, oxygen, blood pressure, comorbidity, lactate, SOFA, APACHE

BEST MODEL: Logistic Regression (Balanced)

RESULTS:
- Accuracy: 55.5% (poor)
- Recall: 57.0% (finds 57% of deaths)
- ROC-AUC: 58.1% (barely better than random)

CONCLUSION:
Vital signs alone cannot reliably predict ICU mortality.
Clinical prediction requires additional data: lab results, medications, time-series trends.

LIMITATIONS OF THIS STUDY:
1. Used only averaged vital signs (no trends)
2. Missing key clinical data (lab results, treatments)
3. Class imbalance (77% survivors, 23% deaths)

FUTURE WORK:
1. Add laboratory results (creatinine, bilirubin, platelets)
2. Use time-series data (trends over 24-48 hours)
3. Include treatment information (antibiotics, ventilation)
4. Collect more balanced dataset

LEARNING OUTCOME:
This project demonstrates that machine learning on limited features produces poor predictions. Real-world AI systems require comprehensive clinical data.
